"Situations The word ''epidemic'' is a constant of disaster situations. The first reports of such situations almost invariably speak of incipient epidemics. This myth must be eradicated once and for all: ''Epidemics do not occur spontaneously after a disaster and dead bodies will not necessarily cause catastrophic outbreaks of disease.'' 67 Some situations, of course, have indeed given rise to genuine epidemics, such as the 1964 malaria epidemic in Haiti following Hurricane Flora. The main danger of an epidemic developing, however, is attributable not to the disaster itself, but rather to the consequences of the disaster. These consequences can be divided into two categories:\n."